{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:43:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:43:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20714"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20714"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.96,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95821"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13590"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78600"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11772"},{"type":"tags","id":"12593"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32675"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95821"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESeptic shock is characterised by complex pathophysiological changes affecting multiple organ systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key pathophysiological mechanism in septic shock?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhanced fibrinolysis due to decreased plasminogen activator inhibitor-1","Decreased production of nitric oxide by endothelial cells","Widespread endothelial activation leading to vascular leakage","Decreased tissue factor production by monocytes","Predominance of anti-inflammatory cytokines over pro-inflammatory cytokines"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn septic shock, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewidespread endothelial activation leading to vascular leakage\u003C/strong\u003E is a key pathophysiological mechanism. Activated endothelial cells loosen their tight junctions, allowing protein-rich fluid to leak into tissues. This leads to tissue oedema and impaired perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced fibrinolysis due to decreased plasminogen activator inhibitor-1\u003C/strong\u003E - Sepsis actually increases plasminogen activator inhibitor-1, which suppresses fibrinolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased production of nitric oxide by endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Nitric oxide production increases in sepsis, contributing to vasodilation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased tissue factor production by monocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Tissue factor production increases in sepsis, promoting coagulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPredominance of anti-inflammatory cytokines over pro-inflammatory cytokines\u003C/strong\u003E - The initial phase of sepsis features prominent pro-inflammatory cytokine production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional effects of endothelial activation include increased nitric oxide production causing vasodilation, upregulation of adhesion molecules, and disrupted microvascular flow regulation. These changes contribute to the shock state and organ dysfunction seen in sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Septic shock involves both pro-inflammatory and counter-inflammatory responses triggered by pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) and damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs).","Endothelial activation in septic shock leads to vascular leakage, tissue oedema, and microvascular dysfunction that impairs tissue perfusion.","Septic shock induces a procoagulant state that can lead to disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) through increased tissue factor production and decreased anticoagulant factors."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; pages 135-137."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78600"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20714"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78600"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:47:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:48:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13590"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95821"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11772"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-11T18:06:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T18:06: